<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Can I modify a Word template to work for multiple employees?</h3>
<p>Yes, but it is time-consuming. You would need to save a copy for each employee, update the name, SSN, pay period, and all calculated amounts for each. If you have more than one or two employees to pay, a dedicated payroll tool (Gusto starts at $40/month, QuickBooks Payroll at $45/month) is more efficient and legally safer than managing individual Word documents. For very small operations with one employee (like a household employer paying a nanny), a Word template can work if you are disciplined about the calculations.</p>

<h3>Does a Word pay stub template work on Mac?</h3>
<p>Microsoft Word for Mac can open and edit .docx pay stub templates without any compatibility issues for basic formatting. However, some templates use Windows-specific fonts that may render differently on Mac. If you notice font substitution issues, change the template font to Arial, Helvetica, or another cross-platform font before entering your information.</p>

<h3>Should I password-protect my completed pay stub Word document?</h3>
<p>If you are sharing the document electronically, converting to PDF before sharing is better than sharing a Word document. PDFs are not editable (without specialized software), which preserves the integrity of the document. Password-protecting the PDF adds an additional layer, but is generally not necessary for submitting to a landlord or lender -- they are not in the business of editing your documents.</p>

<h3>How do I make a Word pay stub look more professional?</h3>
<p>Use consistent fonts (one font family throughout), avoid excessive decoration, and ensure the table borders are clean and even. Match the formatting you see on actual payroll company pay stubs -- simple, clean, tabular layout with clear section headers (Earnings, Deductions, Net Pay, Year-to-Date). Avoid colored backgrounds or unusual fonts. The generator on this page produces a professionally formatted PDF that requires no additional design decisions on your part.</p>

